## Opportunity Conservation Rules

Define how the original strategic opportunity must be preserved across the resulting initiative set.

| ID | Conservation Rule | Meaning | Split Implication |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- full strategic opportunity must be covered
- no unrelated opportunity may be added
- desired capability must remain represented
- risk-reduction purpose must remain represented
- enabled future work must remain represented
- excluded elements require explicit rationale

## Capability Partitioning Rules

Define valid strategic capability boundaries.

| ID | Partitioning Rule | Meaning | Invalid Split Signal |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- each resulting epic owns one coherent capability
- capability ownership must be unambiguous
- implementation phases are not sufficient epic boundaries
- task fragments are not epics
- resulting initiatives must have independent strategic value
- shared capability ownership requires refinement

## Repository Boundary Discovery Rules

Define how repository evidence should inform natural split boundaries.

| ID | Repository Boundary Pattern | Strategic Interpretation | Split Implication |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples of Repository Boundary Pattern:

- domain boundary
- API boundary
- compatibility surface
- platform boundary
- runtime boundary
- data ownership boundary
- workflow boundary
- migration seam
- missing foundation
- validation boundary

Do not include actual repository facts.

## Dependency Derivation Rules

Define how dependencies among resulting initiatives should be derived.

| ID | Dependency Pattern | Derivation Rule | Split Implication |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- foundational capability precedes dependent capability
- semantic model precedes feature use
- compatibility boundary precedes integration
- validation foundation precedes high-risk work
- migration seam precedes dependent modernization
- platform capability precedes downstream roadmap epics
- dependency too unclear requires investigation or blocking

## Split Quality Criteria

Define what makes a split high quality.

| ID | Criterion | High-Quality Split Means | Low-Quality Split Means |
|---|---|---|---|

Include criteria for:

- strategic cohesion
- low coupling
- independent value
- repository alignment
- explicit dependencies
- complete coverage
- no overlap
- future roadmap clarity
- minimal fragmentation
- constraint preservation

## Coverage Rules

Define how the downstream prompt should prove that the resulting initiatives collectively cover the original opportunity.

| ID | Coverage Rule | Required Evidence | Failure Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- every material proposal element assigned exactly once
- every desired capability accounted for
- every strategic risk represented or explicitly excluded
- every dependency assigned or acknowledged
- every non-goal stated when exclusion prevents ambiguity

Failure Handling should explain whether to refine partition, add initiative, merge initiative, or block split.

## Overlap Prevention Rules

Define how to prevent duplicate or ambiguous ownership.

| ID | Overlap Case | Prevention Rule | Required Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- two epics own same capability
- shared infrastructure is implicit
- acceptance responsibility is duplicated
- sibling scopes overlap
- boundary between capabilities is unclear
- one epic consumes another epic’s unfinished capability

## Split Blocking Rules

Define when SplitEpic should refuse to split.

| ID | Blocking Case | Indicates | Required Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Indicates must be one of:

- CreateNewEpic Required
- ReimagineEpic Required
- Strategic Investigation Required
- Roadmap Revision Required
- Insufficient Evidence
- Projection Conflict
- Governance Escalation
- Different Prompt Required

Examples:

- only one coherent capability exists
- split would create task fragments
- no repository-supported boundary exists
- coverage cannot be proven
- overlap cannot be resolved
- dependency graph cannot be determined
- split would violate projection constraints
- split would require changing Core intent
- proposal is not actually a split

## Handoff Requirements For Resulting Initiatives

Define what each resulting initiative must provide to the authoring path.

| ID | Handoff Requirement | Required Content | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|---|

Include requirements for:

- owned capability
- strategic purpose
- source opportunity link
- projection link
- repository grounding summary
- sibling dependency relationships
- non-overlap boundary
- constraints
- major risks
- suggested filename

This section should define handoff requirements only.

Do not include detailed epic authoring rules.

## Traceability Requirements

Define how the split must prove its sources and coverage.

| ID | Traceability Requirement | Required Evidence | Failure Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- original opportunity must trace to proposal and projection
- each resulting initiative must trace to a distinct opportunity element
- each dependency must trace to proposal, projection, or repository evidence
- every excluded element must have rationale
- coverage table must prove no material opportunity was lost
- overlap check must prove no capability is duplicated

